==English==

===Etymology===
Anglo-Saxon ''[[bridd]]'', "young bird", "chick", in general a "young" of any animal.

'''Bird''' is also a now common and not necessarily as wrong perceived misspelling of ''[[burd]]'', probably because ''burd'' has a similar meaning to ''bird'' in reference to women (see definition 3 below).
[[Image:Blue Tit aka.jpg|thumb|right|A small bird, definition 1]]

===Pronunciation===
*bû(r)d, /bɜː(r)d/, /b3:(r)d/

===Noun===
{{en-noun-reg}}

# The common name for the [[class]] of [[animal]]s ''[[Aves]]'' in the [[phylum]] [[chordata]], characterized by being warm-blooded, having [[feather]]s, [[wing]]s usually capable of [[flight]], and laying [[egg]]s; any member of that class.
#:''[[Duck]]s and [[sparrow]]s are birds.''
# {{slang}} A person.
#:''He's an odd bird.''
# {{slang}} '''bird''' is used by a man to refer to a woman he considers sexually attractive. 
#:''Who's that bird?''
# (''originally Cockney rhyming slang''; ''shortened from'' '''[[bird-lime]]''', ''for'' '''[[time]]''') A [[prison sentence]].
#:''He's doing bird.''

